1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 {This move is central to the Closed Sicilian. As in 
many g3 openings, positional battles tend to ensue.} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. 
f4 e6 {White has expanded on the kingside and will seek play on that side of the 
board.} 7. Nf3 Nge7 8. O-O O-O {White has more kingside space, but Black has 
firm control of the central dark squares.} 9. Be3 Nd4 {Taking advantage of his 
central dark sqare control!} 10. Qd2 Rb8 {Preparing b7-b5} 11. Nd1 b5 {Black 
begins to expand on the queenside.} *

