1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {This is called the Grand Prix Attack. It is very 
popular at the amateur level.} g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 {This is one possible 
variation that White can employ, immediately targeting the f7 pawn. It also 
discourages a d7-d5 pawn break.} d6 6. O-O e6 {This is the pawn structure that I 
like to have as Black. The pawn on e6 supports a potential d6-d5.} 7. f5 {White 
tries to open up lines towards Black's king. This move is usually postponed 
until later however.} exf5 8. d3 Nge7 9. Qe1 h6 {White has achieved very little 
and is down a pawn. Black still has to be careful however as White's queen will 
be coming to the kingside to help in White's attack.} *

