[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "black-vs-anti-sicilians-tournament-edition/course/2385, variation/79705"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 d6 6. O-O {White does not 
immediately play f5, which is much more common.} e6 7. d3 Nge7 {Black's current 
set-up will occur in many of my favorite Grand Prix Attack lines. Black's pawns 
are aimed towards the queenside, hence he will aim for qeenside play.} 8. Qe1 
{White intends to bring the queen to the kingside with Qh4 or Qg3.} O-O 9. f5 
{White breaks up Black's pawns.} gxf5 $1 {This move appears to be weakening but 
it is in fact the most accurate because Black can still play Ng6 in the future.} 
10. Qg3 fxe4 11. dxe4 Ng6 {Black blocks the g-file with a good position.} *

