[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "black-vs-anti-sicilians-tournament-edition/course/2385, variation/79698"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 {This is called the Smith-Morra Gambit. 
It can be extremely dangerous to play against if you are not familiar with it. 
However, the well-prepared player should be able to achieve at least equality 
against it.} Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 {This sets up my favorite variation.} 6. Bc4 Qc7 
{This is my favorite variation for Black. I particularly enjoy playing it 
because White is often caught off guard.} 7. Qe2 {O-O is an alternative move 
order.} Nf6 8. O-O Ng4 {This is a very tricky move with which I have caught many 
of my opponents off guard. The idea is that a careless h3?? can be met by Nd4!, 
winning White's queen.} 9. Nb5 {If g3 instead, Black can just continue calmly 
with d6.} Qb8 10. h3 {Nd4 is no longer possible because White can play Nbxd4.} 
Nge5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bf4 a6 {Black is under some pressure but has an extra 
pawn, as is common in the Smith-Morra Gambit.} *

