1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. f3 {This unusual move by White is 
called Prins Variation. White seeks to establish a small edge with a maroczy 
bind.} e5 {Black responds as actively as possible. This move does weaken the 
d5-square and the d6-pawn, but these weaknesses are are well-protected by 
Black's bishops.} 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 {Black's most ambitious response.} 7. Nf5 d5 $1 
{Black gives up a pawn temporarily.} 8. exd5 a6 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Ne3 b5 {Black 
is preparing Bb7, regaining the pawn.} 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. O-O b4 13. Ne4 Nxd5 14. 
Nxd5 Bxd5 {Black has regained the pawn and has a comfortable position.} *

