1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. 
Bg5 e6 {In this case, g7-g6 would lose a pawn.} 9. O-O-O Be7 10. Qd3 Qa5 {Black 
can continue actively.} 11. h4 h6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Black is left with the bishop 
pair, a useful advantage in such positions. Note that Qxd6 is not good for White 
because Black can just respond with Bxc3.} *

